<subSubSection id="C89655E1E34C8059FF70FC55462AFC52" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8033066AE34C8059FF70FC55462AFC52" blockId="7.[178,1085,949,1002]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">Etymology: The specific epithet (Latin, adjective: with two apices) alludes to the shape of the apex of the aedeagus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C89655E1E34C8056FF70FC19451EFDB8" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="1651" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650" type="description">
<paragraph id="8033066AE34C8059FF70FC1945D7FBF2" blockId="7.[178,1086,1017,1098]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">
Description: Small species; body length 
<quantity id="4774AB8FE34C8059FD78FC19472AFBB7" box="[698,782,1017,1039]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650" unit="mm" value="4.8">4.8 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity id="4774AB8FE34C8059FC25FC19401EFBB7" box="[999,1082,1017,1039]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: body dark-brown, except for the reddish-brown elytra; legs pale yellowishbrown; antennae yellowish-red.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8033066AE34C8059FF70FBB947A2FAB9" blockId="7.[178,1086,1113,1281]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">
Head (
<figureCitation id="18B71AEFE34C8059FF35FBB94565FBD7" box="[247,321,1113,1135]" captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[178,1073,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-77@6.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 9-18: Lathrobium barbiventre (9-10), L. rougemonti (11), L. mancum (12-13), and L. bicuspidatum (14-18): (9, 12) female sternite VIII; (10, 11, 13) female tergites IX-X; (14) forebody; (15) male sternite VII; (16) male sternite VIII; (17-18) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 14: 1.0 mm; 9-13, 15-18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303205" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303205/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as broad; punctation rather coarse and moderately sparse, even sparser in postero-median dorsal portion; interstices with shallow microreticulation, but glossy. Eyes weakly projecting from lateral contours of head, slightly more than one third the length of postocular region in dorsal view and composed of approximately 50 ommatidia. Antenna short, 
<quantity id="4774AB8FE34C8059FD50FB2E46C7FB5C" box="[658,739,1230,1252]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
long; antennomere II barely 1.5 times as long as broad, III weakly oblong, and IV-X weakly transverse.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8033066AE34C8059FF70FAF245B2FAC6" blockId="7.[178,1086,1297,1407]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="18B71AEFE34C8059FEE7FAF14554FA9F" box="[293,368,1297,1319]" captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[178,1073,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-77@6.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 9-18: Lathrobium barbiventre (9-10), L. rougemonti (11), L. mancum (12-13), and L. bicuspidatum (14-18): (9, 12) female sternite VIII; (10, 11, 13) female tergites IX-X; (14) forebody; (15) male sternite VII; (16) male sternite VIII; (17-18) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 14: 1.0 mm; 9-13, 15-18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303205" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303205/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) 1.23 times as long as broad and 0.98 times as broad as head; lateral margins subparallel in dorsal view; punctation slightly finer than that of head; impunctate midline broad; interstices without microsculpture, on average somewhat broader than diameter of punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8033066AE34C8059FF70FA6E46E3FA66" blockId="7.[178,1086,1422,1502]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="18B71AEFE34C8059FEC1FA6E4576FA1C" box="[259,338,1422,1444]" captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[178,1073,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-77@6.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 9-18: Lathrobium barbiventre (9-10), L. rougemonti (11), L. mancum (12-13), and L. bicuspidatum (14-18): (9, 12) female sternite VIII; (10, 11, 13) female tergites IX-X; (14) forebody; (15) male sternite VII; (16) male sternite VIII; (17-18) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 14: 1.0 mm; 9-13, 15-18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303205" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303205/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) approximately 0.58 times as long as pronotum, very weakly dilated posteriad; humeral angles marked; punctation shallow, fine, and sparse; interstices without microsculpture. Hind wings completely reduced.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8033066AE34C8059FF70FA0E47A6F986" blockId="7.[178,1086,1518,1598]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1650">Abdomen 1.08 times as broad as elytra; punctation fine and moderately dense, only slightly sparser on tergites VII and VIII than on tergites III-VI; interstices with distinct microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII without palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8033066AE3438056FF05FF3B463CFE62" blockId="8.[178,1085,218,475]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">
: protarsomeres I-IV moderately dilated; sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="18B71AEFE3438056FD3BFF3A4761FF48" box="[761,837,218,240]" captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[178,1073,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-77@6.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 9-18: Lathrobium barbiventre (9-10), L. rougemonti (11), L. mancum (12-13), and L. bicuspidatum (14-18): (9, 12) female sternite VIII; (10, 11, 13) female tergites IX-X; (14) forebody; (15) male sternite VII; (16) male sternite VIII; (17-18) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 14: 1.0 mm; 9-13, 15-18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303205" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303205/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) moderately transverse, posteriorly with small median impression, this impression with weakly modified setae, posterior margin weakly concave in the middle; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="18B71AEFE3438056FCEAFEF54756FE93" box="[808,882,277,299]" captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[178,1073,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-77@6.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 9-18: Lathrobium barbiventre (9-10), L. rougemonti (11), L. mancum (12-13), and L. bicuspidatum (14-18): (9, 12) female sternite VIII; (10, 11, 13) female tergites IX-X; (14) forebody; (15) male sternite VII; (16) male sternite VIII; (17-18) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 14: 1.0 mm; 9-13, 15-18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303205" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303205/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) weakly transverse, with shallow postero-median impression, this impression without pubescence in the middle, posterior excision weakly asymmetric and in slightly asymmetric position, approximately 0.15 times as deep as length of sternite; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="18B71AEFE3438056FCA2FE8D47F5FE3B" box="[864,977,365,387]" captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[178,1073,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-77@6.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 9-18: Lathrobium barbiventre (9-10), L. rougemonti (11), L. mancum (12-13), and L. bicuspidatum (14-18): (9, 12) female sternite VIII; (10, 11, 13) female tergites IX-X; (14) forebody; (15) male sternite VII; (16) male sternite VIII; (17-18) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 14: 1.0 mm; 9-13, 15-18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303205" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303205/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">Figs 17-18</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity id="4774AB8FE3438056FC23FE8D4019FE3B" box="[993,1085,365,387]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.07" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" unit="mm" value="1.07">1.07 mm</quantity>
long, slender, and weakly asymmetric in basal half; ventral process apically distinctly bifid; dorsal plate reduced; internal sac without appreciable structures, aside from a membranous ring-shaped structure.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8033066AE3438056FF05FE0B451EFDB8" blockId="8.[199,314,490,512]" box="[199,314,490,512]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">: unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C89655E1E3438056FF70FDEF472DFC12" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8033066AE3438056FF70FDEF45C3FD6D" blockId="8.[178,1086,527,725]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">
Comparative notes: Based on the morphology of the aedeagus and the male secondary sexual characters, 
<taxonomicName id="478C7DE9E3438056FE37FDCD46BFFDFA" authorityName="Assing &amp; S" authorityYear="2013" box="[501,667,556,578]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicuspidatum">
<emphasis id="B2F8DA78E3438056FE37FDCD46BFFDFA" box="[501,667,556,578]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">L bicuspidatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is undoubtedly closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="478C7DE9E3438056FBEAFDCD45D3FDD8" authority="TICHOMIROVA 1976" authorityName="TICHOMIROVA" authorityYear="1976" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="molodovae">
<emphasis id="B2F8DA78E3438056FBEAFDCD4505FDD8" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">L. molodovae</emphasis>
TICHOMIROVA 1976
</taxonomicName>
and allied species, which are distributed in the Russian Far East and East Siberia, and which were attributed to the 
<taxonomicName id="478C7DE9E3438056FC8DFD8847F4FDC5" box="[847,976,615,637]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sibiricum">
<emphasis id="B2F8DA78E3438056FC8DFD8847F4FDC5" box="[847,976,615,637]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">L. sibiricum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group by 
<bibRefCitation id="E41D7B9BE3438056FF70FD654577FD22" author="RYVKIN A" box="[178,339,644,666]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" pagination="179 - 234" refId="ref6757" refString="RYVKIN A. B. (2007): A review of Lathrobium species of the sibiricum group (Insecta: Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Bulletin de l'Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique, Entomologie 77: 179 - 234." type="journal article" year="2007">RYVKIN (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. It is reliably distinguished from them only by the morphology of the aedeagus. For illustrations of the male and female sexual characters of other species of this group see 
<bibRefCitation id="E41D7B9BE3438056FE87FD2045C7FD6D" author="RYVKIN A" box="[325,483,703,725]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" pagination="179 - 234" refId="ref6757" refString="RYVKIN A. B. (2007): A review of Lathrobium species of the sibiricum group (Insecta: Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Bulletin de l'Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique, Entomologie 77: 179 - 234." type="journal article" year="2007">RYVKIN (2007)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8033066AE3438056FF70FD04472DFC12" blockId="8.[178,1085,740,938]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">
The only other 
<taxonomicName id="478C7DE9E3438056FEA5FD044612FD42" box="[359,566,740,762]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B2F8DA78E3438056FEA5FD0445FAFD42" box="[359,478,740,762]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">Lathrobium</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
known from the Chinese province 
<collectingRegion id="4248C888E3438056FC0CFD0447DEFD42" box="[974,1018,740,762]" country="China" name="Jilin" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">Jilin</collectingRegion>
is 
<taxonomicName id="478C7DE9E3438056FBEAFD054635FCAF" authority="LI &amp; CHEN 1990" authorityName="LI &amp; CHEN" authorityYear="1990" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jingyuetanicum">
<emphasis id="B2F8DA78E3438056FBEAFD05456AFCAF" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">L. jingyuetanicum</emphasis>
LI &amp; CHEN 1990
</taxonomicName>
, which was described from the Jingyuetan National Park to the southeast of Changchun, a locality of relatively low altitude separated from the 
<typeStatus id="5F37B8C8E3438056FF1EFCDD452CFCEA" box="[220,264,829,850]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="478C7DE9E3438056FE4BFCDD4614FCEA" authorityName="Assing &amp; S" authorityYear="2013" box="[393,560,828,850]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicuspidatum">
<emphasis id="B2F8DA78E3438056FE4BFCDD4614FCEA" box="[393,560,828,850]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">L. bicuspidatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by nearly 
<quantity id="4774AB8FE3438056FD6BFCDC46D9FCEA" box="[681,765,828,850]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" unit="km" value="300.0">300 km</quantity>
. Unfortunately, aside from an indication of the body size (
<quantity id="4774AB8FE3438056FE12FCB94628FCD7" box="[464,524,857,879]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
) and a reference to eye size (one sixth as long as postocular region), the original description of 
<taxonomicName id="478C7DE9E3438056FDB9FC984713FC35" authorityName="LI &amp; CHEN" authorityYear="1990" box="[635,823,888,909]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jingyuetanicum">
<emphasis id="B2F8DA78E3438056FDB9FC984713FC35" box="[635,823,888,909]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">L. jingyuetanicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is practically devoid of relevant information and does not include any illustrations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C89655E1E3438056FF70FC594030FBB1" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8033066AE3438056FF70FC594030FBB1" blockId="8.[178,1086,953,1034]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">
Distribution and natural history: Thetypelocalityissituatedin the Chang Bai Shan in the southeast of Jilin province, very close to the border with 
<collectingCountry id="F89B46FAE3438056FBC1FC3644D7FBB1" name="North Korea" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">North Korea</collectingCountry>
. The 
<typeStatus id="5F37B8C8E3438056FEE8FC1445A7FBB2" box="[298,387,1012,1034]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected from under stones at an altitude of nearly 
<quantity id="4774AB8FE3438056FC03FC144034FBB1" box="[961,1040,1012,1034]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="1651" unit="m" value="2200.0">2200 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
